  "prompt": "What ever happened to Mad Cow Disease?",
  "response": "Mad Cow Disease, or Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), was a significant concern in the 1980s and 1990s, particularly in the United Kingdom. Here's a brief overview of what happened:\n\n1. Peak of the crisis: BSE was most prevalent in the UK during the late 1980s and early 1990s, with over 180,000 cattle infected.\n\n2. Human impact: The disease could be transmitted to humans through consumption of contaminated beef, causing a variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD).\n\n3. Global response: Countries implemented strict regulations on cattle feed, testing, and slaughter to prevent the spread of the disease.\n\n4. Decline: Rigorous control measures significantly reduced the number of BSE cases. In the UK, cases peaked in 1992 and dramatically declined afterward.\n\n5. Current status: BSE is now extremely rare. The last confirmed case in the UK was in 2015, and global incidents have been minimal in recent years.\n\n6. Ongoing precautions: Many countries still maintain strict testing and prevention protocols for cattle to ensure food safety.\n\nWhile Mad Cow Disease is no longer a major public health threat, the agricultural and food safety industries continue to monitor and prevent potential outbreaks.",
